report.measDesc: Topology enforced. Trail features must be covered by features in TransportationLine. Trail features cannot self-intersect.

prcStep.stepDesc: Data updated to integrate with TransportationCartography data developed by Theresa deBoer. The geodatabase was upgraded to ArcGIS10 format. Metadata imported, upgraded, and updated. Topology rebuilt and validated, and all topology errors addressed.

This update was prompted by the recent development of a system of “Greenway” trails in the developed areas of the park, along with a need to distinguish and name the individual trails in the developed areas that have been previously been clustered (e.g. “Residential” trails). Vicki Stinson and Mark Nebel developed an initial delineation and naming scheme that was presented to the Park Leadership Team (PLT) in January, 2012. Based on PLT feedback, some of the trails were re-delineated and/or named. Trails in the School, Albright, and Rec Center areas were field-checked and verified with a Trimble GeoXH GPS receiver. Several new Greenway trails, the re-routed Arizona Trail, and the new Shoshone mule trail were also field mapped using GPS during April-July 2012. This version of the residential area Trails has been provided to the PLT for final approval.
All trail segments that had been previously mapped via Recreation Grade GPS (i.e. “Garmin”) or had been mapped from other low-resolution sources (e.g. DRG topographic maps) were visually checked against newly acquired 2010 NAIP imagery and/or 2009 high resolution GCMRC imagery (river corridor). Where these trail segments were visible in the new imagery, they were re-mapped accordingly.
Some North Rim trails and roads between The Basin and the Widforss Point Trail were updated based on their visibility in LIDAR data from SCPN I&M.
All trail lengths were recalculated, and all trails were routed and/or recalibrated. Topology was enforced and errors were corrected for the entire Transportation feature dataset.
Updates include minor corrections or updates based on recent project work.

Compiled ancillary data that show some trail locations: a. DRG files of USGS topographic maps at 1:24,000, 1:100,000, and 1:250,000 scales b. NAIP imagery, 2005 and 2007 (1 m) c. High resolution developed areas imagery, 2007 (15 cm) d. National Geographic 'Trails Illustrated' maps of the Grand Canyon e. Internet sources

Compiled existing available trails data. Known existing datasets include: a. SDE "Trails_Routes" feature class. Legacy GRCA trails and routes data, derived primarily from 1:100K USGS topographic maps, last updated in 2007 by Chuck Sypher. (Trails are mapped, marked on the ground, and maintained by NPS staff. Routes are NOT officially mapped, marked on the ground, or maintained by NPS staff. This layer represents updates completed through May 2007 by Chuck Sypher.) b. Li Brannfors (Garmin) GPS data, in a shapefile from Eric Gdula ("Trails_Routes_Li.shp"). Li walked many trails for recreation and mapped them with his personal Garmin recreation grade GPS receiver. c. Feature class "Trans_Line" compiled by Theresa deBoer in 2009, from existing data sources and Theresa's own (Trimble) GPS trail mapping ("Theresa.mdb"). Theresa's mapping was done using a Trimble GeoXH Resource grade GPS receiver and high-resolution (15 cm) DOQ's. d. Feature class "Trans_Line" compiled by Theresa deBoer in 2010, containing Developed Area mapping, including roads and trails ("GRCA_Bldgs_and_Trans_2010.mdb"). Theresa's mapping was done using a Trimble GeoXH Resource grade GPS receiver and high-resolution (15 cm) DOQ's. e. SDE "Roads" feature class contains lines for roads, including roads that have been converted to trails. f. FMSS export of managed and maintained trails, courtesy of Jeff Dyer. g. "Trails_Routes_ap.shp" shapefile from Arnie Peterson contains edits made by Arnie in 2009-10 to the SDE "Trails_Routes" feature class. h. Draft Grand Canyon National Park Wilderness Plan contains a list of Park trails. i. "Kanab Plateau Map.pdf", from Kirstin Heins, is a scanned (4/6/2010) map of Grand Canyon National Monument roads, some of which are now trails. j. Historic trails files from Mike Anderson, retired GRCA Historian. k. Draft Grand Canyon Wilderness Management Plan (1998) contains a list of GRCA trails. l. Draft Federal Trail Data Standards (May 19, 2008). m. GRCA Compendium Version 2005.doc. n. Shapefile "PhantomTrails.shp", from Theresa deBoer, contains 2008 GPS data for the Phantom Ranch area.

Developed a master list of all GRCA managed and unmanaged trails and their known classifications and attributes. There currently is not any official maintained list of Park trails or their classification and attributes. The FMSS database contains a listing of trails and some attributes, but trails staff (Rich Goepfrich, Jeff Dyer) are not certain how this list came into existence, and they warn that it is currently not considered complete or accurate. Other documents, e.g. the Draft Grand Canyon National Park Wilderness Plan and the GRCA Compendium, have lists of trails, roads converted to trails, and some classification, but they are also not considered complete or current (per Kirstin Heins). Published Park brochures also have some trail descriptions or show trail locations. The various lists sometimes conflict. Additional trails were identified by GRCA staff.

Created a trails feature class and populated with the best available spatial data for identified trails. Using data from all available sources (see previous process steps), relocated trail feature segments using the best available data. Professional judgment on the part of the editor was ultimately used to determine the most reliable source. In general, the following hierarchy of preferred data sources was followed: a. Trail is visible on 2007 High Resolution imagery; Digitize b. Trail mapped with resource or higher grade GPS; Import mapped segments c. Trail is visible on 2007 NAIP Imagery; Digitize d. Trail is visible on 2005 NAIP Imagery; Digitize e. Trail is mapped with recreational grade GPS; Import mapped segments f. Trail is represented on 1:24,000 DRG topographic map; Digitize g. Trail is represented on 1:100,000 DRG topographic map; Digitize h. Trail is represented in a legacy dataset, but is from an unknown source; Import mapped segments
Reviewed legacy spatial trail lines that are from unknown sources or are entirely unattributed, to determine if they represent lines that should be mapped.

Worked with key GRCA staff stakeholders as an informal Trails Working Group to reach consensus on trail names, classification, location, extent, and attributes. Trails Working Group members include: Mark Nebel, Kirstin Heins, Rich Goepfrich, Theresa deBoer, Mike Anderson, Mike Kearsley, Mark Wunner, Rachel Bennett, and Linda Jalbert. Other staff that assisted with reviews and data included Todd Seliga, Jeff Dyer, and Robin Tellis.
Attributed trail features. Calculated trail length measures in feet and miles, and calibrated routes. Created and validated topology, and corrected errors.

Some Trails, particularly in the Corridor, have improved locations, based on review of and on-screen digitization of, recently acquired high quality imagery, especially 2010 NAIP. A new attribute, SurfaceMaterial, was added and populated. All trail lengths were recalculated and Trail routes recalibrated. Metadata imported and updated.
Edited Waldron Trail to match Wilderness Boundary, per information from Linda Jalbert. Recalculated lengths and recalibrated routes. Updated metadata. Confirmed Datum transformation.
Projected dataset to the NAD83 datum (from NAD83 AZ HARN). Validated projection. Updated metadata.
Changes were made to the Bright Angel trailhead area to incorporate new construction completed this year.

Trails within the extents of the GCMRC 2005 and 2009 high-resolution (18cm) Colorado River corridor imagery, and some parts of trails outside this extent (per 2010 NAIP imagery), were edited to improve their spatial precision, where visible on these images. Trails features thus improved include Beamer, New Hance, Hance Creek, Hermit Creek, Boucher, Bright Angel, Clear Creek, Deer Creek, East and West Tonto, Rim, Kaibab Greenway, Monument Creek, Nankoweap Granary, North and South Bass, North and South Kaibab, Phantom Ranch, River, Saddle Canyon, Tanner, Tapeats Creek, Thunder River, Whitmore, and others. The Escalante, Secret Beach, and Unkar Delta Trails were added as Trails (Escalante had previously been a “Route”).
Edited and newly added Trail lengths were re-calculated and calibrated. Topology validated and errors corrected. Metadata updated.
